# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: south-australian-national-football-league
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1869-south-australian-football-season] The 1869 South Australian football season was the first year of interclub football in the colony of South Australia.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1869-south-australian-football-season] In Adelaide, prior to the establishment of the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) in April 1877, the football season was largely a series of independent club matches and challenge games rather than an organized league season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1869-south-australian-football-season] The unaffiliated era was from 1869 to 1876.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1869-south-australian-football-season] The Old Adelaide Football Club, formed in 1860, was the leading club in Adelaide during the 1860s.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1869-south-australian-football-season] Australian rules football began in Melbourne in 1858, however from 1860 to 1872 the Adelaide club played what appears to be a game a cross between association football and rugby using a round ball.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1869-south-australian-football-season] Adelaide played intraclub and interclub football in South Australia until 1873, when it had disputes with Kensington Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club over standardizing the rules.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] Port Suburban renames to Woodville on 11 May 1870.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] proclaiming the founding of the 'Port Adelaide Cricket and Football Club'.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] The **1870 South Australian football season** was the first year of interclub football in the colony of South Australia.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] Prior to the establishment of the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) in April 1877, the football season was largely a series of independent club matches and challenge games rather than an organized league season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] The unaffiliated era was from 1870 to 1876.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] On Thursday 26 April 1860 the Adelaide Football Club was formed at the Globe Inn Hotel, Rundle Street with John Brodie Spence chairing the meeting.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] It was thereby the first football club established in South Australia.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] The **Port Suburban Football Club** changed its name to "The Woodvilles" at a meeting held at the Ford's Hotel on Wednesday 11 May 1870.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] Several new members were proposed, and the following officers elected :— Captain, J.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] The Football Club played home games at the reserve (now located in St Clair) adjacent to the Woodville Railway Station.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] The reserve was also used by the Port Adelaide Athletics Sports Club.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] The **Young Australian Football Club** was established on the 11 May 1870, in North Adelaide at the Royal Oak Hotel.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] It was reported that a dozen persons were present and Mr.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] Wyly was appointed Secretary and Treasurer, and Messrs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] Mellor, Harrison, Holthouse, Simms, and Randall the committee.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] Blue and white were decided upon as the colors.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1870-south-australian-football-season] It was decided to challenge the Port Suburban Club for the opening game.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] The **1871 South Australian football season** was the second year of interclub football in the colony of South Australia.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] The opening game of football was played in the afternoon of Saturday 15 April 1871, on the North Park Lands, between the Adelaide and Port Adelaide Clubs, the Concordia Band having been engaged.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] The following were the twenty Adelaide players selected: — Messrs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] Aldridge, Brock, Conigrave, Colley, Chambers, Calf, Dale, Dalton, Higgins, Harrison, Jackson, Milne, Masters, Monteith, Nesbit, Randall, Sharpe, Sparks, Townsend, and Watson.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] On 27 May 1871 it was reported His Excellency the Governor consented to take the office of President of this Club, and Lieutenant Fergusson (Private Secretary) purposed joining as a member.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] The Alberton and Queenstown Football Club was formed at the annual meeting held on 24 April 1871 of the Alberton and Queenstown Cricket Club.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] The following officers were chosen for the year: President — Mr.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] The Club numbered 30 members and was financially in a good position.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] The club played its opening game on 28 April 1871 at the ground adjoining the Port Gasworks at Kingston-on-the-Hill.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] Formby, Grandfield, Le Messurier, Martin, Parker, Riscely, A.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/1871-south-australian-football-season] Closing game was played at Glanville on Saturday 9 September 1871.
