[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The **South Australian National Football League**, or **SANFL** (/ˈsænfəl/ or *S-A-N-F-L*), is an Australian rules football league based in the Australian state of South Australia.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] It is also the state's governing body for the sport.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Originally formed as the South Australian Football Association on 30 April 1877, the SANFL is the oldest surviving football league of any code in the world.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] For most of its existence, the league was considered one of the traditional "big three" Australian rules football leagues, along with the Victorian Football League and West Australian Football League.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SANFL has always been a single-division competition, and with the admission of the Adelaide Crows reserves in 2014, the season returned to a 10-team, 18-round home-and-away (regular) season from April to September.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The top five teams play off in a final series culminating in the grand final for the Thomas Seymour Hill Premiership Trophy.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The grand final had traditionally been held at Football Park in October, generally the week after the AFL Grand Final, though this was altered ahead of the 2014 season, resulting in Adelaide Oval hosting the grand final in the penultimate weekend of September.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The semi-professional league is considered the strongest competition after the fully professional Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The league is also responsible for the management of all levels of football in the state.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This includes junior football, country football, amateur football and specific programs rolled out across schools, indigenous communities (including the APY Lands in the state's north) and newly arrived migrant communities.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SANFL owned Football Park, formerly the largest stadium in South Australia.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The stadium, which opened in 1974, was primarily used for Australian Football League matches up until 2013 and had a capacity of over 51,000 prior to being demolished.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The stadium was the headquarters for the league from 1974 to 2013.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SANFL competition is the second highest attended Australian rules football league behind the AFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The first recorded game of any "football" in South Australia was that of 'Caid' played in Thebarton by people of the local Irish community in 1843 to celebrate St Patrick's Day.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1844, there was debate amongst the South Australian Legislative Council whether it be allowed that "foot-ball" be played on Sundays, with arguments against preferring the quiet worship of God.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1859, the Gawler Institute ran a rural fete which included a game of football being staged.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The earliest recorded Australian rules football club in South Australia was Adelaide Football Club (unrelated to the modern day Adelaide Football Club), formed in April 1860.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] An advertisement, sponsored by John Acraman, W.J.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Cussen noted that group had already gathered 30 members.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The club initially only played internal matches between players located North and South of the River Torrens.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] By the early 1870s a number of new clubs were formed.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In addition to the Old Adelaide Club, Port Suburban (founded in 1868 and renamed Woodville in 1870), Port Adelaide and Young Australians both formed in 1870 and Kensington were the principal clubs that were organising interclub matches.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The early years of interclub football began to be dogged by arguments over which set of rules to adopt.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] A meeting of three delegates from each of the three clubs—Adelaide, Kensington and Port Adelaide— was held on 10 March 1873, with Charles Kingston from Adelaide voted as chair in an attempted to draw up a standard code of playing rules.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] However, after a match between Port Adelaide and Kensington in July 1873, it was remarked that neither side understood the rules clearly.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] As the years progressed, there became a growing push for uniformity and structure in South Australian football.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On Wednesday 22 March 1876, a meeting of the South Adelaide Football Club, which had formed the previous year, was held at the Arab Steed Hotel.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] There was a good attendance, and officers and Committee for the season were elected.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Dissatisfaction was expressed relative to the rules by which matches were conducted last season, and the Secretary was instructed to communicate with the various Clubs in order to arrange for regulations.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] It was remarked that scarcely a game was played last season without some misunderstanding arising, some playing by the Old Adelaide Club rules, and others the Kensington Club rules.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] After a lengthy discussion the meeting adjourned to receive a report from the Secretary and Committee.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Country clubs had also been established at Kapunda (1866), Gawler (1868) and Willunga (1874) and the Adelaide-based clubs would sometimes be hosted by these clubs principally on Public Holidays.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] These 3 country clubs would also send delegates to the meetings which formed the South Australian Football Association in 1877.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] A meeting of those interested in football was held at the Prince Alfred Hotel on Thursday evening, July 20, 1876, to consider the question of a uniform code of rules to be adopted by the various Clubs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] There were 56 persons present, including representatives from the Old Adelaide, South Adelaide, Woodville, and Victorian Clubs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Kingston, in explaining the object of the meeting, mentioned that a circular had been issued about six weeks previously by the Kensington Football Club, calling upon the Clubs in and around Adelaide to appoint delegates to consider the question of adopting a uniform code of rules.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Nothing, however, had followed the issuing of the circular, and the meeting that evening was called in consequence.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] He was extremely pleased to see so large an attendance, as it augured well for a revival of the manly game, which, owing to what he considered a foolish modification of what were known as the old Adelaide rules, had sadly degenerated.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The regulations generally known as the Kensington roles had during the last two seasons in which they had been adopted only provoked continual disputes when matches were engaged in.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] He then moved that the rules played in Victoria should be considered.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] They differed but slightly from the old Adelaide rules.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] If such rules were adopted he felt sure that football would be carried on far more successfully than had been the case lately, and there would be a greater probability of intercolonial matches being arranged, as he hoped would be the case at no distant date.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Crooks having seconded the motion, the Melbourne Football Rules were considered seriatim and adopted In their entirety, with the exception of Rules 6, 7, and 8. which were amended in a manner to assimilate somewhat to the old Adelaide rules.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] An addition to Rule 6 provided that no player having claimed his mark should run with the ball.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Rule 7 was struck out, and the following substituted:— " The ball may be taken in hand at any time, but the player shall be liable to be held or thrown until he drops it." An addition to Rule 8 provided that pushing from behind should only be allowable when the player was running.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The chief alterations in the game as hitherto played in Adelaide are the dispensing with the cross bar and top rope in favour of two upright posts of unlimited height, and the substitution of an oval football for the round one.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Perkins were appointed a Committee to confer with the Secretaries of other Clubs with a view to securing their concurrence in the action taken by the meeting.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] They were also empowered to consider the question of offering a Challenge Cup for next season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1877, following an initial meeting called by Richard Twopeny on Thursday 19 April 1877 at Prince Alfred Hotel delegates from 13 of South Australia's football clubs met to develop a uniform set of rules and establish a governing body.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The South Australian Football Association was formed at a meeting called at the Prince Alfred Hotel in King William Street, Adelaide on 30 April 1877, and adopted rules similar to those used in Victoria upon the urging of Charles Cameron Kingston.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The use of an oval ball, bouncing the ball, and pushing from behind forbidden amongst the rules agreed at the meeting.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The clubs that sent 2 delegates each to the meeting were: South Park, Willunga, Port Adelaide, Adelaide, North Adelaide, Prince Alfred College, Gawler, Kapunda, Bankers, Woodville, South Adelaide, Kensington, and Victorian.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The inaugural 1877 SAFA season was contested by 8 clubs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] A total of 4 games were also played by Adelaide and Woodville when they were hosted twice each by the country clubs Gawler and Kapunda on public holidays but these weren't counted in the premiership table at the end of the season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] South Adelaide and Victorian were declared joint Club Champions.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1878, a brand new club Norwood was formed following the entire collapse of Woodville by a number of former players and it joined the Association for the season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] An end of season match on 31 August between a combined Adelaide Team from the Association against a combined team from the 3 country clubs – Gawler, Kapunda and Willunga was played on the Adelaide Ground.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] With the Adelaide team winning 5 goals to 1.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1880 it was proposed to create a Junior Football Association, similar to the Cricket Association, from Clubs such as the North Parks, St.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Peter's College, Prince Alfred College, Royal Parks, West Torrens, Woodville, South Suburban, Hotham, and Middlesex.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1881 - Adelaide and Kensington merged at a meeting held on 11 April it was decided that the colour of the merged club be black-and scarlet guernsey, hose, and cap, and navy blue knickerbockers.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SAFA was notified in writing of the amalgamation which was read at a meeting held on 27 April 1881.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The merged club played 4 games before resigning on 1 June.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1882 - The first general meeting of the committee of the Junior Football Association was held at the Prince Alfred Hotel on Monday evening, March 27.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] All the clubs - North Parks, North Adelaide Juniors, Kensington, Kent Town, Albion, Triton, and West Torrens were represented.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Later some of these clubs would be admitted to the Senior Association - North Parks would merge with North Adelaide Juniors and join as Adelaide in 1885 and West Torrens as West Adelaide in 1887.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In May 1884 - A proposal to merge the senior Association (SAFA) with the Junior Association (called the Adelaide and Suburban Association) was started with 5 delegates from each Association to confer as what steps can be taken but was in the end rejected by the SAFA.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Of the original senior clubs – Bankers (1877), Woodville (1877), Adelaide and Kensington (1881 after merging), South Park (1884), Victorian (1884) - i.e.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] 6 of the original 8 had all left the competition by the start of the 1885 Season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Only Port Adelaide and South Adelaide hadn't folded or resigned and together with Norwood which had joined in 1878 these 3 senior clubs dominated the competition.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1885, a new senior Adelaide Club joined the competition and won the Premiership the following season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The club was formed from a merger of North Adelaide Juniors (which had renamed to Adelaide in 1884) and North Parks.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Upon merger and admission the Club took up the Old Adelaide colours of Black and Red.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1887 another three Clubs were admitted Hotham and West Adelaide and the only country team ever admitted Gawler Albion but all only lasted for a few seasons.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] West Adelaide folded after just one season (1887), their resignation was accepted at the Annual General Meeting held on 5 April 1888, as they were unable to get a team together.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] At the same meeting permission was given for Hotham to change their name to North Adelaide and for Gawler to remove the word Albion from their name.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 1888 SAFA season was started under a cloud, as a dispute arose when the old senior clubs Adelaide, Port Adelaide and South Adelaide all withdrew and resigned from the SAFA and created their own Association and had advertised for other clubs to join them.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The split meant Norwood was the only senior club left in the original SAFA along with the two new clubs Gawler and Hotham (renamed North Adelaide) which had just joined the previous year.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] To settled the dispute the three remaining SAFA clubs were then invited to apply to join this new Association which had a number of new rules.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] A junior club Medindie (which would rename itself North Adelaide Football Club in 1893) had applied to join this new United Association but were willing to withdraw their application if this helped resolve the dispute.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] However, they were accepted along with applications from Norwood, North Adelaide (Hotham) and Gawler and this meant a seven team competition was maintained.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Medindie was a foundation member in 1885 of the South Australian Junior Football Association, before spending the 1886 and 1887 seasons competing in the Adelaide and Suburban Football Association.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The first meeting of the United Football Association was held on Wednesday evening 9th May 1888.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The result was the old South Australian Football Association being wound up and a new one formed termed 'The South Australian **United Football Association'**.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Hotham which renamed to North Adelaide for 1888 merged with Adelaide for the 1889 season reducing the competition to six clubs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On Friday 5 April 1889 At the Annual General Meeting held on Friday 5 April 1889 in the Trades Exchange with all the clubs present the United Football Association renamed itself to South Australian Football Association.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Gawler after its 4th season notified the Association in writing in April 1891 that it would no longer be joining (principally due to being given only 5 home games at Gawler and 10 away games in Adelaide for the 1890 season).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1889 it had created its own Junior League consisting of 3 clubs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In May 1892, the Gawler Association again was affiliated with the SAFA.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Subsequently, it tried to rejoin the competition a number of times but was rejected.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1913, it was admitted but withdrew before the season started.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On 14 March 1893, at a meeting held at Temperance Hall, North Adelaide Medindie renamed itself to North Adelaide Football Club.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In March 1894, Adelaide withdrew from the Association in writing before the season commenced.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This reduced the number of senior clubs to just 4 - Port Adelaide, South Adelaide, Norwood and North Adelaide (originally called Medindie).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In March 1895, a new club called Natives applied to join as the 5th Senior Club.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] It was formed from players from various districts and a group of former Port Adelaide players from a junior club called Port Natives.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] "The Natives" was adopted so as to prevent any feeling that it was confined to any given locality.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Principally the members were drawn from the Port Natives, who were the premiers of the Adelaide and Suburban Association.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] After initially having their application refused.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] At a meeting on the 5th April 1895 the Natives then submitted a list of 50 players to show their strength.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] They were then admitted by 13 votes to 5 against.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This new senior club would rename itself and be called West Torrens in 1897 with the introduction of the Electoral System.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1896, North Adelaide and the Natives were permitted to field 23 players (3 extra players).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] At an Association committee meeting held on 10 August 1896, a proposal was tabled to introduce having no more than eight clubs in the association and that all clubs and any new players be zoned based on the state electoral districts.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] At an adjourned meeting on Monday 26 Oct 1896, South Adelaide agreed to be zoned to the Electoral of East Adelaide and delegates from the Port Natives Football Club stated they would rename and take the West Torrens District.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] (which brought it in to line with the VFA).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On 5 April 1897, The Association approved the application of the current West Adelaide Football Club to join the SAFA from the Suburban Association and The Native Football Club (1895–1896) altered its name to West Torrens Football Club,.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Despite the constitution allowing 8 clubs based on the Electoral Districts the Association comprised six clubs until the turn of the century.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The three newer clubs (North, West Adelaide and West Torrens) continued to struggle against the older three clubs (Norwood, Port and South Adelaide).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In the First Round both West Adelaide (vs Norwood) and West Torrens (vs Port Adelaide) failed to score for the whole game.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] There were also a number of walkovers throughout the season when the newer clubs failed to field a team.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1898, the Magarey Medal was awarded to the fairest and most brilliant player for the first time.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] At a meeting held on Monday 8 May 1899 with a large number of delegates present the Secretary was instructed to write to the Gawler and Port Pirie Associations to inform them that their applications to join the SAFA would not be entertained this year as purely electorate football was being tried.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In mid to late 1900 there was growing interest to form a senior club in the Sturt Electoral District based around Unley to join the SAFA.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1900, North Adelaide won the Grand Final against South Adelaide breaking the dominance of the 3 old traditional Clubs – Norwood (11), South Adelaide (8) and Port Adelaide (3) which together had won 22 of the first 23 premierships (1877–1899).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] West Adelaide followed three straight wooden spoons from 1904 to 1906 with four out of the five premierships from 1908 to 1912 (including Championship of Australia in 1908 and 1913), the most successful period in West Adelaide's history.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1902, Port Adelaide adopted its now famous black and white colours.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1907, the association changed its name to the South Australian Football League.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1910 Adelaide University Football Club made an application to enter the competition as the 8th team.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This led to players such as Jack Londrigan leaving league clubs such as Sturt in anticipation for a university league team.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] However the application was ultimately rejected by the competition out of fear a university side would compromise the electorate system, also referred to as zones, introduced to equalise the state competition.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On 2 December 1912, the Gawler Football Association was granted admission to the league to fill the zone based on the vacant 8th Electoral District Barossa.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On 3 March 1913 it was confirmed the team would be called Gawler and its colors were registered as follows: Black jersey with pink hoop, white knickers and black-and-pink hose.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] However, just before the start of the 1913 season the association notified the league in writing that it had to withdraw due to loss of prominent players from their district and the depressed condition of the sport locally.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The University Club, the 1911 and 1912 premiers of the South Australian Amateur Football League (SAAFL), applied to fill the vacancy created by Gawler's withdrawal but was turned down by a unanimous vote of the delegates.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SAFL maintained competition for the first two years of World War I, 1914 and 1915, with Sturt winning their first premiership in 1915, but from 1916 the competition was suspended and did not resume until 1919.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] However, a league competition was formed in 1916 called South Australian Patriotic Football League by the SAFL Clubs and a number of non-AFL Clubs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The league existed for 3 seasons (1916, 1917 and 1918) and Games held were used to raise funds for the war effort.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SAFL was opposed to the formation of the Patriotic League and refused to recognise it during and after World War I.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Sturt won the first premiership of the post-World War I era, beating North Adelaide in the Challenge Final replay after a Draw occurred in the 1919 SAFL Grand Final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] At a meeting on Monday 19 April 1920 the SAFL defined that part of Sturt district west of South Road as a new district and admitted a newly formed Glenelg to the B Grade for 1920.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] It became 8th club in the senior league in 1921 but started poorly with five consecutive wooden spoons.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1927, the South Australian Football League was renamed the South Australian National Football League.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Everyone of the 8 clubs won at least one premiership during the 9 years from 1927 to 1935, including Glenelg which their first premiership in 1934 would be the only success in their first 52 years.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Prior to World War 2 Port Adelaide won three premierships in the period 1934–1939, appearing in 6 successive grand finals.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SANFL continued normal competition for the first few years of World War II, but from 1942 to 1944 for 3 seasons the clubs merged on a geographical basis.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Post World War 2 was dominated by Norwood who won 3 flags in 5 years between 1946 and 1950.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide, led by Fos Williams, dominated the 1950s winning seven premierships, including a record setting six Grand Final wins in a row from 1954 to 1959.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This record also matched Norwood's six in a row in 1883, set before the advent of regular Grand Finals.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Previously a country team from Gawler had competed for 4 seasons from 1887 to 1890.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] South Adelaide were also requesting to consolidate their zone and to be potentially based at Kensington Oval.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On 20 March 1950 Salisbury Football Club made an application to join the SANFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Applications by Burnside and Woodville were also rejected by the SANFL in June 1950.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In February 1953, The Mayor of Woodville again raised the issue of having a team admitted.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Citing a large number of players from West Torrens and Port Adelaide actually resided in the City of Woodville.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Aitken agreed, but only if West Adelaide was the winning team that year.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] However Port Adelaide coach and captain, Fos Williams, said that he expected his team to win, and the men agreed that if Port Adelaide won, their colours would be painted on the chimney.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide won that year, so the chimney was painted in black and white vertical stripes, but Williams suggested that a red stripe be painted below the black to honour the runners-up.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1959, after doubting whether the club was viable as a league team, the SANFL granted South Adelaide a substantial area of the newly developing southern Adelaide suburbs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Also the SANFL finally expanded to 10 teams by admitting a new club Central District based at Elizabeth in the outer north and Woodville an existing amateur league club based in the north west of metropolitan Adelaide.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The newly admitted Clubs would play 5 years in the Reserves (B Grade) before joining the A Grade in 1964.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Central Districts qualified for the finals in 1971, 1972 finishing 3rd in both years losing in the preliminary to Port Adelaide.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1979 they collected the minor premiership but lost both finals to again finished 3rd.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Woodville qualified for the finals for the first time in 1979 and finished in 5th.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Their most successful season was 1986 in which they 3rd which was followed up by a 5th place in 1987.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide continued their dominance of the competition from 1962 with three more premierships in 1962, 1963 and 1965.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] They would contest 7 successive Grand Finals from 1962 to 1968.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Their successive premierships was broken by South Adelaide which went from wooden spooners in 1962 and 1963 to the win the Premiership in 1964 (their first since 1938) by defeating Port Adelaide.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1965, Port Adelaide exceeded Norwood for the most premierships when they collected their 23rd Cup.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] A resurgent Sturt under coach Jack Oatey won five straight premierships from 1966 to 1970, sharing a fierce rivalry with Port Adelaide whom they met in four consecutive Grand Finals from 1965 to 1968.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Sturt began the 1970s by defeating Glenelg in a rain-affected Grand Final by 21 points.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] North Adelaide secured back-to-back premiership victories over Port Adelaide in 1971 and 1972 and defeated VFL premier Carlton by one point in the end-of-season Championship of Australia match.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Glenelg won their 2nd premiership, and first since 1934, defeating North Adelaide by 7 points in 1973 in the highest scoring Grand Final 21.11 (137) to 19.16 (130).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide continued their success, winning two premierships themselves (1977, 1979), and finishing lower than 3rd only once for the decade.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On 4 May 1974, Central District and North Adelaide played the first game at newly opened Football Park at West Lakes.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] SANFL moved its administration to the new stadium, and 58,042 attended the first Grand Final at the ground later that year, with Sturt defeating Glenelg by 15 points despite kicking into a stiff breeze in the last quarter after leading by 5 points at three-quarter time.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 1975 season was highlighted by Glenelg's score of 49.23 (317) against Central District, with a winning margin of 238 points which was larger, at that time, than the previous highest score ever recorded by a side in a single game.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1976, Sturt defeated Grand Final favourites Port Adelaide by 41 points in front of a record ticketed Football Park crowd of 66,897.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Norwood won the 1978 premiership in their centenary year by beating Sturt in the Grand Final by one point after Sturt had lost just one game for the entire season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] During the 1970s, an increasing number of SANFL players moved to Victoria to play in the VFL competition.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The only year being the exception was 1983 when West Adelaide defeated Sturt in the Grand Final for their first premiership since 1961.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In the decade between 1979 and 1989 only three clubs, Central District, Woodville, both admitted to the SANFL in 1964, and West Torrens were the only clubs not to reach at least one grand final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The exodus of high quality players to the VFL accelerated in the 1980s.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Only Collingwood (1979, 1980 & 1981), Melbourne (1988) and Geelong under first year expat coach and former Woodville player Malcolm Blight (1989) would reach a VFL grand final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1981 the VFL rejected a SANFL bid to enter a composite South Australian team to its competition.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Night football was introduced in 1984 after floodlights were installed at Football Park.The SANFL introduced a player retention scheme in 1988 in an attempt to maintain the quality of the competition in the face of falling attendances.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The tradition of painting the colours of the premier and runners-up was maintained at the Hindley Street premises of SA Brewing until its closure in 1980, before transferring to the Thebarton site, which was rebadged "West End".
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] On 31 July 1990, Port Adelaide surprised the SANFL by making an independent bid to join the AFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The SANFL was left with little option but to submit its own bid to enter the AFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In a thirty-minute meeting the SANFL formed the Adelaide Football Club.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The Adelaide Football Club, nicknamed the Crows, debuted in 1991 wearing the state colours of navy blue, red and yellow.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] While the Adelaide Crows enjoyed crowds of over 40,000 every week and dominated local media coverage, crowds at local SANFL matches suffered substantially.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1994 after a tender process put to all the SANFL clubs, the Port Adelaide Football Club secured a licence to enter the AFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide chose the nickname of 'Power' since 'Magpies' was already used by Collingwood.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide wished to maintain its presence (as the Magpies) in the SANFL, which was agreed to on the basis that Port Adelaide's SANFL and AFL entities operate independently.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The club in the SANFL was renamed "Port Adelaide Magpies Football Club" to reflect this separation.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] In 1995, South Adelaide after playing their home games in Adelaide since the formation of the club in 1876 moved to Noarlunga Downs.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Port Adelaide dominated the SANFL in this time, contesting 10 Grand Finals in 12 years between 1988 and 1999 – winning 9 premierships (1988–1990,1992,1994–1996,1998–1999) and losing just the one Grand Final in 1997 to Norwood (their 27th Flag).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This Port Adelaide dominance in the period is somewhat of an aberration.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] It should be kept in context with the hasty formation of the Adelaide Crows in 1991.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] During this period many of the remaining SANFL clubs' best players were seconded to the Adelaide Crows, whereas the Port Adelaide list was largely left intact due to the conflict that ensued around the Port Adelaide rank-breaking bid to join the expanded VFL competition as a stand-alone club.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The Woodville and West Torrens Clubs merged at the end of the 1990 Season and won their first premiership in 1993 against Norwood.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Between 1900 and 1999 Port Adelaide contested a total of 59 Grand Finals – winning the flag 33 times to bring their total to 36.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] There was a changing of the guard as the new century started.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] For more than 100 years one of Port Adelaide, Norwood, North Adelaide or Sturt appeared in every Grand Final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The year 2000 saw the two newest teams Central District and Woodville-West Torrens played off in the Grand Final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Only Sturt (2002) and Woodville-West Torrens (2006 & 2011) interrupted Centrals' run during this period.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Centrals played in 28 Finals games between 2000 and 2011 for a total of 25 wins (which included 12 consecutive 2nd Semi Final wins) and just 3 losses (2002,2006,2011 Grand Finals).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Under-age divisions were restructured, with under 17 and under 19 competitions dissolved in favour of under 16 and under 18 leagues, the latter coming into line with Victoria's TAC Cup competition and under the sponsorship of McDonald's would be known as the Macca's Cup.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The former would become the Macca's Shield, the season length is around half that of the other levels of competition.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Night games would become a feature at Elizabeth Oval, with Central District hosting Saturday night matches from 2006.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 2012 SANFL season saw Centrals exit the finals for the first time since 2000 without contesting in the Grand Final, this time after finishing 2nd at the end of the minor round with defeats by West Adelaide in the Qualifying and then North Adelaide in the 1st Semi-Final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 2012 and 2013 premierships were both won by Norwood, firstly defeating West Adelaide by 49 points to win their 28th flag and then subsequently defeating North Adelaide by 40 points for their 29th flag.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This was the first time Norwood had won back to back flags for 90 years when coincidentally they also beat West Adelaide (1922) and North Adelaide (1923).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] These moves caused some furore in some fan circles.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 2013 Grand Final was the last SANFL match at AAMI Stadium, with SANFL league headquarters to remain at AAMI but the finals to return to the new and improved Adelaide Oval from 2014.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Ahead of the 2014 season, the AFL-based Adelaide Football Club were granted a licence to field a reserve team in the competition, increasing the number of teams in the league to 10.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] As a result of the Magpies becoming the Power's reserve team, and the inclusion of the Crows reserves team in the SANFL in 2014, the other SANFL clubs will lose their AFL contracted players as those contracted to the Crows or Power will move to play exclusively for those clubs in either league.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Norwood defeated arch-rivals Port Adelaide Magpies by 4 points in the 2014 Grand Final to secure their 30th Flag and 3rd in a row (2012–2014) for the first time since 1887–89.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Norwood's dominance of the competition would end in the 2015 season, eliminated at the first week of the finals as West Adelaide ended a 32-year premiership drought with their five-goal defeat of Woodville-West Torrens in the Grand Final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 2016 and 2017 premierships were both won by Sturt their 14th and 15th Flags and first since 2002.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 2018 premiership was won by North their 14th Flag and first since 1991.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 2019 premiership was won by Glenelg their 5th Flag and first since 1986 ending a 33-year premiership drought.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This meant within the last 10 seasons 7 different clubs had won a premiership.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Only the two original clubs of the competition South Adelaide (last flag in 1964) and Port Adelaide (last flag in 1999) had not won a premiership flag in at least the last 20 years (excluding the Adelaide Crows reserves team).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The 2020 season was originally scheduled to run from April until September; however its commencement was delayed to June 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The number of clubs participating in the season was reduced to eight, as Adelaide Crows AFL Reserves and Port Adelaide Magpies AFL Reserves were barred from fielding their reserves teams by the Australian Football League.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This is the first time in its history that Port Adelaide did not compete in the SANFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The season was conducted with 14 rounds and a Final Four.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] Woodville-West Torrens defeated North Adelaide in the Grand Final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] This was the last time that the top two teams' colours were painted on the West End brewery's chimney, before that site's closure.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p01] The Woodville West Torrens Eagles were the 2021 SANFL Premiers, after they defeated Glenelg.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] On 10 September 2013, Port Adelaide and the SANFL agreed to a model to allow all its AFL-listed players (not selected to play for Port Adelaide Power in the AFL) to play for Port Adelaide Magpies in the SANFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Adelaide AFL Club formed in 1990 created a reserves team in 2014.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Three country clubs Gawler, Kapunda and Willunga were originally affiliated with the SAFA when it formed in 1877.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] They did not play in the Home and Away Season but games would be organised by the metropolitan Clubs usually on Public Holidays with the Country Club hosting.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Only the Gawler club would eventually compete in the home and away season when it merged with another club in the town in 1887 called Gawler Albion which was formed in 1880.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Games are generally hosted at suburban grounds throughout Adelaide.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The league's revenue is derived from its paid attendance, media and payments from both the Adelaide Crows and Port Adelaide AFL clubs for use of Adelaide Oval.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The SANFL is classed as a semi-professional competition.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In 2008 the league had a salary cap of $400,000 (excluding service payments).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] This is the second highest in Australia for an Australian rules football competition, after the AFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of the SANFL is Darren Chandler, who replaced Jake Parkinson in the role in 2020.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The players of the SANFL are represented by the SANFL Players' Association.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] South Australian leagues (including the SANFL) award two points for a win, and one for a draw.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Elsewhere in Australia generally four points are awarded for a win and two for a draw.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In addition percentage is calculated as "For" ÷ "Against" × "100".
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The SANFL match-day program is called the *South Australian Football Budget/Football Budget* and is sold at all SANFL matches.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] A special edition is produced for the grand final.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The SANFL competition's "match of the round" was broadcast weekly in South Australia on ABC Southern (ABC1 South Australia).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Until early 2008, it was also broadcast nationally on ABC2 television.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In 2012, nationwide SANFL match replays resumed on ABC2.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Match replays are also available nationally on ABC iView.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In 2007, the SANFL measured a record 1,415,000 total television viewers.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The SANFL competition is covered by local radio stations Life FM (live) and 5RPH (live).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] ABC Local Radio and 5AA broadcast the SANFL Finals Series.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In 2013, the SANFL signed a three-year deal with the Seven Network to broadcast weekly matches on 7mate from the start of the 2014 season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] This marked the league's return to commercial television for the first time since Channel 9 broadcast the SANFL in 1992.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Seven-SANFL partnership was most recently extended in 2026.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Although SANFL crowds now competes heavily with the two AFL national league clubs, the SANFL still has the second highest attendance of any Australian rules football league and the highest attendance for any regional league of any football code.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] It continues to publish attendance figures.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The record attendance for an SANFL fixture was set at the 1976 SANFL Grand Final between Sturt and Port Adelaide at Football Park which saw 66,987 crammed into the stadium, though some estimate the crowd to have been as high as 80,000 with thousands turned away at the gates.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The largest attendance for a minor round fixture was set in Round 19, 1988 for a double header at Football Park.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] 38,213 fans saw Sturt play Port Adelaide in the early game while reigning premiers North Adelaide faced ladder leaders Central District in the late game.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The record suburban ground attendance was an estimated 24,000 who saw Sturt and Norwood at Unley Oval on 9 June 1924.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] A verified attendance of 22,738 saw Port play Norwood at Alberton in Round 11, 1977*.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The following are attendance figures since 1991.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Grand Final winners each season are presented the **Thomas Seymour Hill Premiership Trophy**, named after administrator Thomas Seymour Hill.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Lewis Memorial Trophy**, awarded annually since 1962, recognises the best combined record in all levels of SANFL competition.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In the event of a draw, half of the points allocated for a win in that grade are awarded to each club involved.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Prior to the creation of the women's league, the trophy was awarded on the basis of performances in the men's league, reserves league and under-18 league.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Magarey Medal is awarded to the fairest and most brilliant player in the SANFL each season and is the oldest individual football award in Australia.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The medal was originated by and is named after William Ashley Magarey who, in 1897, was the inaugural chairman of the South Australian Football Association (as the SANFL was then known).
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In 1898, in an effort to stamp out rough play and improve respect of umpires, Magarey instituted the medal to be awarded to the player deemed by umpires to be the fairest and most brilliant for that season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The inaugural winner of the medal was Norwood's Alby Green.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Magarey presented every medal until he died in 1929, with West Adelaide's Robert Snell the last to receive the medal during Magarey's life.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Magarey Medal is still awarded to the fairest and most brilliant SANFL player each season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Reserves Magarey Medal recognises the standout performers in the seconds or Reserves.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] It is not unusual for the Reserves Magarey winner to play only half a season in the 'seconds' and the rest of the season in their club's league team.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Ken Farmer Medal, much like the Coleman Medal in the AFL, is awarded to the league player with the most goals in a season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] There are also the McCallum and Tomkins Medals, which up until the 2008 season were awarded to the best and fairest players of the U-17 and U-19 divisions respectively.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] These awards were merged in 2009 when the two under-age competitions were replaced with an U-18's league, similar to those adopted in the West Australian Football League and the VFL's TAC Cup.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The first winner of the newly created McCallum–Tomkins Medal was South Adelaide's Luke Bowd.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Jack Oatey Medal is awarded to the player voted best on ground in the SANFL Grand Final, first awarded in the 1981 premiership decider to Russell Ebert of Port Adelaide.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In the same year, the Fos Williams Medal was also commissioned to recognise the standout performer for South Australia in interstate football, the first of which was awarded to Peter Carey of Glenelg.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Despite State of Origin football being dropped from the AFL calendar after 1999, the medal continues to be awarded to the best player for the SANFL representative team in interstate football.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Shearman Medal, since its inception in 2000, is awarded to the player voted by the League's senior coaches on a 5–4–3–2–1 basis each game of the home-and-away season.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The Bob Quinn Medal is awarded to the player voted best afield in the Anzac Day matches between the Grand Finalists of the previous year.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Commissioned in 2002, the medal was first won by James Gowans of Central District.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Also in 2002, the SANFL created the South Australian Football Hall of Fame to recognise the players, coaches, umpires, administrators and journalists who had made a significant contribution in the SANFL.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The inaugural class of 2002 saw 113 inductees into the Hall of Fame and included such greats as Russell Ebert, Ken Farmer, Barrie Robran, Malcolm Blight, Fos Williams, Brian Faehse, Lindsay Head, Neil Kerley, Rick Davies and Jack Oatey.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] In February 2017, the SANFL followed the example of VFL Women's in Victoria, and created a state-based women's Australian rules football competition replicating its men's league.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] The SANFLW expanded over the following two years, and is now played by eight of the SANFL clubs between February and May, with Adelaide and Port Adelaide not participating.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Due to the timing of the league, most SANFLW players are not contracted to clubs in the semi-professional AFL Women's national competition, though some AFLW-listed players do play occasional matches for their respective club.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Aside from the senior SANFL competition, the league has operated a reserves competition since 1919 (such a competition has existed since 1906), and has also operated four underage competitions.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Under-19s and Under-17s competitions were run from 1937 and 1939 respectively until 2008, when the league merged these competitions to form the Under-18s competition (initially known as the Maccas Cup) from 2009: it introduced an Under-16s competition the following year.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Neither Adelaide nor Port Adelaide field teams in these competitions.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] Adelaide has elected not to field teams, while Port Adelaide shut down their underage teams in 2014 and their reserves team in 2018.
[src:south-australian-national-football-league/south-australian-national-football-league-p02] For a full list of reserves and under 16–19 premiers, see List of SANFL premiers#Minor grades.
